## Why we weren’t doing it before

The old sim either **traced a few dozen** insns or **ran forever** in spin-waits. A loop like ICON’s delay:

```text
0135: ... compare counter ...
013f: jl  short
0144: jmp 0135      ; spin until condition
0146: continue
```

…is “correct” forever if the condition never becomes true (timer/keyboard/not emulated). Burning millions of instructions there doesn’t help format RE.

## What we do now

**Tight backward `jmp` / `jcc` only** (not `LOOP`/`CX` — those are finite and must finish for Pascal RTL):

1. Body runs normally up to **`--loop-limit`** times (default **10000**).
2. After that, the back-edge is **forced to fall-through** → sim continues past the spin.
3. Only short spans: **`--loop-span=XX`** (default **100h** bytes). Long backward jumps (epilogues, big retries) are left alone.

```bash
# Default: counting loops usually OK; infinite spins get cut
./dumpexe --simulate --bp=int:21,continue ICON.EXE

# “Run body once, then continue” (aggressive — can break real multi-iter jcc loops)
./dumpexe --simulate --loop-limit=1 --loop-span=40 ICON.EXE

# Disable
./dumpexe --simulate --loop-limit=0 ICON.EXE
```

You’ll see lines like:

```text
[loop-skip] 1008:0144 -> 0135 (span Fh) after 10001 takes (limit 10000); fall-through 0146
```

With defaults on ICON we already get **video mode INT 10**, **INT 21 traffic**, and that wait loop skipped instead of hanging forever.

## Tradeoff (important)

| Mode | Good for | Risk |
|------|----------|------|
| `--loop-limit=1` | Escape spin-waits fast | Early exit of real `jcc` loops → wrong state / garbage code |
| default `10000` | Most RE | Slow pure delays still burn ~10k×body |
| `0` | Faithful counting | True infinite waits never exit |

So: **yes, execute the loop a bounded number of times, then continue** — not by “skipping the body,” but by **allowing N takes of the back-edge, then taking the exit path**. That’s the usual RE compromise between authenticity and progress.

If you want the next refinement: only skip when the same edge is **hot** (e.g. >N takes with almost no other IPs) so rare multi-iter `jcc` loops are safer while pure spins still die quickly.

