That matches the tech stack perfectly.

ICON is **1984 Macrocom**, **CGA mode 01h (40×25 color text)** with a **custom 8×8 font** and hybrid “draw with characters” approach — not EGA/VGA bitmaps. So you get:

- Chunky 8×8 cells  
- A small tile/font set (`BA.DAT` ~2 KB)  
- Maps as cell data, not pixel art  
- Same era aesthetic as a lot of early PC CRPGs: functional, not pretty  

The README even warns graphics can look “garbled” because the font isn’t stock CGA. So “simple and ugly” isn’t a failure of DOSBox — it’s authentic Quest for the Ring.

That actually helps RE: fewer asset formats, tiny tile bank, text-buffer-centric rendering. Ugly assets are easier to reverse than a polished VGA title.

