### Sourcer (V Communications)
- **What:** Multi-pass **x86 disassembler** for DOS (and related 16-bit code), aimed at turning binaries into readable assembly listings.
- **Why people liked it:** Multiple analysis passes, better **code vs data** separation than simple one-shot disassemblers, labeled output, comments/structure closer to something you could reassemble or study.
- **Version you mentioned:** **8.01 (2001)** is commonly cited as the last commercial release.
- **Era:** Peak usefulness for 80s–90s DOS games/apps (MZ EXE, COM, overlays) — same problem space as ICON / dumpexe.

### Relation to what you’re doing
| Need | Sourcer | dumpexe / DOSBox path |
|------|---------|------------------------|
| Static listing of 16-bit EXE/OVL | Strong historically | You’re building modern equivalents |
| Runtime (FCB, modes, live DS) | Not its job | DOSBox debugtrace / mem dumps |
| Pascal MT+ overlays | Listing yes; semantics still manual | Same |

So yes: familiar, and still a valid **reference style** for multi-pass DOS disasm. It’s not something I can run as a licensed product in-session unless you have a local install.

