### What gets “polluted”

| Where overlay is drawn | Window / agent screenshot | Staging image capture | **B800 / VRAM / mem dump** |
|------------------------|---------------------------|------------------------|----------------------------|
| **Host only** (SDL after guest texture) | Yes — grid visible | Often yes (post-render) | **No** — guest memory untouched |
| **Guest VRAM** (write cells into B800) | Yes | Yes | **Yes — dumps are contaminated** |

For reverse-engineering we want **host-side only**:

- Screenshots (and your pathfinding) show a **cell grid** so we can count steps.
- **`DUMPSCREEN` / `B800` / `DUMPMEM` stay pure guest state** — no fake grid chars, no extra attrs.

Drawing the grid *into* mode-01h text RAM would help the eye once, then every machine-code note becomes “is this the game or the overlay?”

### Practical design

1. **Overlay = host compositor** (lines on top of the scaled frame in `PresentFrame`).
2. Toggle: key combo + config + socket (`OVERLAY on/off`).
3. Grid = **BIOS text cells** (40×25 for ICON play), not “hero pixel bbox” unless we later mark a multi-cell hero footprint on top of that cell grid.
4. Optional: **thicker every N cells**, **col/row numbers** — still host-only.
5. Agent screenshots keep the grid; RE dumps do not.

So: yes, overlays will show up in **pictures of the window**; they must **not** show up in **video-memory dumps**. That’s the whole point of doing it in DOSBox’s presenter rather than in ICON’s VRAM.

